title: For Sale:  H&K P7M10
postcontent: Heckler & Koch P7M10 with the beautiful factory nickel finish. These are great shooting pistols and were introduced in the early 1990’s. The P7M10, like the 9mm P7 models, is a fixed barrel, gas delayed, striker fired blowback pistol. They are of superb quality and craftsmanship. In my opinion, the P7 series pistols are the finest handguns HK ever built in their 50-year history. Accuracy is excellent, due to the 4” fixed barrel and the low bore axis makes them point very naturally. The P7M10 is the model that was brought onto the market for the then-new 40S&W cartridge. As the name would suggest, the magazine holds 10 rounds. In typical HK fashion, it was built to very high standards of excellence. This particular example was made in West Germany in 1992. It has the factory nickel finish and is in outstanding condition inside and out with a mint bore. I’ve owned the gun since 2008. I don’t shoot much 40S&W, so it was shot less than 200 rounds by me. It was perfectly reliable with minimal recoil. I have no idea how much it was shot prior to me owning it. Judging from the great condition, I would guess not too much. Both the steel and the grips are like new, This is perfect for the Heckler & Koch collector or German pistol collector. It’s also perfect for someone who wants a great shooting pistol for the range. This HK will last a lifetime. Its built like a tank. It comes as shown with no box or papers and one magazine. These guns are getting harder and harder to find, especially in this condition. Value has gone up on these over the years and will continue to, so buy for now and the future. I ship everything Fedex 2-day from an FFL.

title: For Sale:  VEPR 7.62x39
postcontent:
I have a new and unfired VEPR 7.62x39 for sale. It has the 16.5” heavy barrel. If you are unfamiliar with the VEPR, they are Russian built by Molot. Molot builds the heavy RPK machine guns which is what this is. It has the same extra heavy reinforced receiver and heavy profile barrel as the RPK, but it is chambered in 7.62x39 and has the shorter barrel. The thick barrel is cold hammer forged, chrome lined, and has a muzzle nut over the threads to protect them.  The heavier barrel aids in heat dissipation as well as makes it more accurate. The wood on this is the more beautiful grade that came on the more expensive ones. The VEPR is the Cadillac of the AK world and has a nice finish. It will come with both a 5 and a 10 round magazine, cleaning rod, cleaning kit, box, and paperwork.
If someone were looking to convert this to pistol grip configuration, all you would have to do is change out the buttstock and install a traditional stock and pistol grip. You do not have to move the trigger group and guard like on the Saiga’s. Everything is already in place.
This is not one of the less expensive ones that were imported with the crappy wood. I am asking for $775 for this beauty. You can call or text me at 210-seven 22-zero six 33. If the ad is still up, I still have it.

title: For Sale:  CZ 75 P-01 9mm
postcontent: CZ 75 P-01 9mm, BNIB, two magazines.  Buy this handgun online at www.copsgunshop.netProduct Description The CZ P-01 is a compact, aluminum-framed 9mm designed for LE and Military duty, but its compact size and the reduced weight due to its forged alloy frame make it ideal for discrete carry as well. Equipped with a decocker, the P-01 provides convenience for those who prefer hammer-down carry. With a heavy first-round trigger pull, any additional shots are a light, crisp single action. The P-01 was the first CZ model to benefit from updated manufacturing technology at CZ’s Uhersky Brod factory. Since the time of its introduction (designed in 2001, NATO-approved in 2003) the production upgrades have been rolled out to the rest of the CZ 75 family and several new rifle models as well. These upgrades mean the components of the P-01/P-06 are completely interchangeable with every other P-01/P-06, with no individual fitting needed. This required some very careful re-design so that the reliability and accuracy were not impaired. With an integral 1913 accessory rail on its dust cover, the P-01 easily accepts any of the industry-standard lights and lasers to assist with low-light use. After 3 years of some of the most aggressive small arms testing ever, the CZ P-01 won the honor of replacing the CZ 75s previously used by the Czech National Police. Reliability:  The U.S. Army “Mean Rounds Between Failure” (MRBF) requirement is 495 rounds for 9mm pistols. During testing of the CZ P-01, the average number of stoppages was only 7 per 15,000 rounds fired. This is a .05% failure rate or an MRBF of 2142! For many years, the P-01 carried an NSN engraved on its frame, making it the first NATO-spec pistol ever available to the public. Recently, the factory decided to upgrade the slide stop spring which in turn means the current models may or may not carry an NSN.
